Ford GoBike System
¶

Exploratory Data Analysis - by Donia Djerbi
¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes informations about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for the periode of February 2019. The purpose of the analysis is to answer the following questions:

Questions for Analysis¶

01 - At what hour, day and which station have the highest number of bicycle hires?\ 02 - What type of users take more trips? and what gender as well?\ 03 - Does the age affect the number of trips.\ 04 - Does sharing the bike for all the trip affect the trip duration?\ 05 - What is the average trip duration and distance?

Lets calculate the distance between the start station and the end station, which could means also the travelled distance.

In [20]:
def calc_distance(x):
    start = (x.start_station_latitude, x.start_station_longitude)
    end = (x.end_station_latitude, x.end_station_longitude)
    return geopy.distance.geodesic(start, end ).km
df['distance'] = df.apply(calc_distance, axis = 1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consists of 183340 bike trips data with 15 features(duration_min, distance, start_dayofweek, start_hour, end_dayofweek, end_hour, start_station_name, end_station_name, user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip, Age, bike_id). There are 5 categorial data types, 3 object data types and 6 numerical data types and one datetime.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in figuring out what are the most important features that have an impact on the choice of the start station.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the variables of the ride starting data as well as the user's type could have a strong effect.

# Create a function to plot histograms 
def hist_func(S,A, Title):
    binsize = S
    bins = np.arange(df[A].min(), df[A].max()+binsize, binsize)
    plt.figure(figsize = (5,4))
    fig = sb.histplot(data=df, x = A, bins=bins, color='#15616d')
    plt.xlabel(A)
    title = plt.title(Title)
    plt.show()
    return fig

#Create a function to plot histograms on a log scale
def log_function(data, B, A, Title):
    log_binsize = 0.1
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(np.log10(df[A].min()), np.log10(df[A].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

    plt.figure(figsize=[5, 5])
    fig = plt.hist(data = data , x = A, bins = bins, edgecolor='k')
    plt.axvline(m, color ='r', linestyle='dashed')
    plt.axvline(median, color ='g', linestyle='dashed')
    plt.axvline(m+std, color ='y', linestyle='dashed')
    plt.axvline(m-std, color ='y', linestyle='dashed')
    plt.xscale('log')
    plt.xlabel(Title)
    plt.ylabel('Counts')
    plt.show()
    return fig
In [30]:
log_function(df, 0.1, 'duration_min', 'Distribution of bike ride duration in minutes');

We can see that the average duration of bike rides is 12 minutes however the median duration is 8 minutes. The hystogram presents an asymmetric normal distribution with a standard deviation of 29.9 wich means that the data is spread.\ The mean is higher than the median, so, it is a right-skewed data. Now, I want to find out the outliers.

In [31]:
from scipy.stats import iqr

# Calculate the interquartile range IQR of the ride duration per minutes then calculate the lower and the upper thresholds
iqr = iqr(df['duration_min'])
lower_threshold = np.quantile(df['duration_min'], 0.25) - 1.5 * iqr
upper_threshold = np.quantile(df['duration_min'], 0.75) + 1.5 * iqr

# Subset the data frame to find rides with duration above and below thresholds
outliers = df[(df['duration_min'] < lower_threshold) | (df['duration_min'] > upper_threshold)]

# Create a function to calculate and plot percentages
def percentage(A):
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data=df, x= A, color=base_color);


    # Recalculating the type_counts just to have clarity.
    type_counts = df[A].value_counts()

     # get the current tick locations and labels
    locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=90) 

    # loop through each pair of locations and labels
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

         # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
        count = type_counts[label.get_text()]
        sum_days = df[A].value_counts().sum()
        pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/sum_days)

        # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
        plt.text(loc, count+2, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'black')

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The rides duration in minutes took on a large range of values, so I changed the x axis to a log axis. After transformation, the data presents an asymetric normal distribution.\ It seems that there is a data accuracy issue. there is no logic between ride duration ,the distance and the age. for the bivariate analysis, I will categorize the ages then, I will calculate the speed to have a clearer understanding.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When plotting the distance distribution, some distances are equal to zero and there were outliers. First I dropped the rows with distance equal to zero.Then, I looked for outliers, there were only one equal to 69 Km. After dropping the outlier, the data presents a right-skewed distribution. I dropped ages above 80 years for analysis consistancy.

In [70]:
# Create a function to plot violin plots
def violin_func(X , Y, Title, xlab):
    V = sb.violinplot(data=df, x= X, y=Y , color = '#00A9A5')
    V.set(xlabel = None)
    plt.ylabel('Start hours')
    plt.xlabel(xlab)
    plt.title(Title);

What are the rush hours per day of the week?¶

In [72]:
violin_func('start_dayofweek','start_hour','Distribution of the start hours of trips per day of the week', None)

As shown in the violin plot above, during weekdays the start hours of rides tend to be in the morning around 8 am or in the evening around 5 pm, which means at rush hours. However, during weekends, the bicycle hires tend to be all the day with an importante hires the afternoon.

Distribution of start hours Vs. ages category¶

In [73]:
violin_func('Ages_category','start_hour', 'Distribution of the start hours of trips per Ages category', 'Ages category' )

It can be seen for ages below 60 years, that the bicycle hires are for the rush hours to go for work or to study. However for the riders above 60 years we can assume that the bicycle hires is equally distributed.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There is a relationship between the start hour and the day of the week. On the weekdays, the number of bicycle hires increases during the rush hours between 8 to 10 am and 5 to 7 pm. However, on weekends, there is no specific rush hour, bicycles are being hired all the day especially from 10am to 7pm.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Interestingly, only subscribers have high number of trips.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [79]:
cat_means = df.groupby(['user_type', 'member_gender']).mean()['duration_min']
cat_means = cat_means.reset_index(name = 'num_var2_avg')
cat_means = cat_means.pivot(index = 'member_gender', columns = 'user_type',
                            values = 'num_var2_avg')
sb.heatmap(cat_means, annot = True, fmt = '.1f',
           cbar_kws = {'label' : 'Average duration (min)'}, cmap='viridis_r')
plt.ylabel('Member gender')
plt.xlabel('User type');

As expected, customer females have longer trips with an average of 15.8 minutes. Now, I want to explore the effect of the day and the hour on the choice of the station.
